I'm going to create a new Django project with Django REST Framework and set up a messaging app. Here's the step-by-step process:
Step 1: Create and Navigate to Project Directory
# Create project directory and navigate to it
mkdir messaging_app
cd messaging_app

Step 2: Create Virtual Environment (Recommended)
# Create virtual environment
python -m venv venv

# Activate virtual environment
# On Windows:
venv\Scripts\activate
# On macOS/Linux:
source venv/bin/activate

Step 3: Install Dependencies
# Install Django and Django REST Framework
pip install django djangorestframework

Step 4: Initialize Django Project
# Create new Django project
django-admin startproject messaging_app .

Step 5: Configure Django REST Framework in settings.py
Edit messaging_app/settings.py:
"""
Django settings for messaging_app project.
"""

from pathlib import Path

# Build paths inside the project like this: BASE_DIR / 'subdir'.
BASE_DIR = Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent

# SECURITY WARNING: keep the secret key used in production secret!
SECRET_KEY = 'django-insecure-your-secret-key-here'

# SECURITY WARNING: don't run with debug turned on in production!
DEBUG = True

ALLOWED_HOSTS = []

# Application definition
INSTALLED_APPS = [
    'django.contrib.admin',
    'django.contrib.auth',
    'django.contrib.contenttypes',
    'django.contrib.sessions',
    'django.contrib.messages',
    'django.contrib.staticfiles',
    
    # Third party apps
    'rest_framework',
    
    # Local apps
    'chats',  # We'll create this next
]

MIDDLEWARE = [
    'django.middleware.security.SecurityMiddleware',
    'django.contrib.sessions.middleware.SessionMiddleware',
    'django.middleware.common.CommonMiddleware',
    'django.middleware.csrf.CsrfViewMiddleware',
    'django.contrib.auth.middleware.AuthenticationMiddleware',
    'django.contrib.messages.middleware.MessageMiddleware',
    'django.middleware.clickjacking.XFrameOptionsMiddleware',
]

ROOT_URLCONF = 'messaging_app.urls'

TEMPLATES = [
    {
        'BACKEND': 'django.template.backends.django.DjangoTemplates',
        'DIRS': [],
        'APP_DIRS': True,
        'OPTIONS': {
            'context_processors': [
                'django.template.context_processors.debug',
                'django.template.context_processors.request',
                'django.contrib.auth.context_processors.auth',
                'django.contrib.messages.context_processors.messages',
            ],
        },
    },
]

WSGI_APPLICATION = 'messaging_app.wsgi.application'

# Database
DATABASES = {
    'default': {
        'ENGINE': 'django.db.backends.sqlite3',
        'NAME': BASE_DIR / 'db.sqlite3',
    }
}

# Password validation
AUTH_PASSWORD_VALIDATORS = [
    {
        'NAME': 'django.contrib.auth.password_validation.UserAttributeSimilarityValidator',
    },
    {
        'NAME': 'django.contrib.auth.password_validation.MinimumLengthValidator',
    },
    {
        'NAME': 'django.contrib.auth.password_validation.CommonPasswordValidator',
    },
    {
        'NAME': 'django.contrib.auth.password_validation.NumericPasswordValidator',
    },
]

# Internationalization
LANGUAGE_CODE = 'en-us'
TIME_ZONE = 'UTC'
USE_I18N = True
USE_TZ = True

# Static files (CSS, JavaScript, Images)
STATIC_URL = 'static/'

# Default primary key field type
DEFAULT_AUTO_FIELD = 'django.db.models.BigAutoField'

# Django REST Framework configuration
REST_FRAMEWORK = {
    'DEFAULT_PERMISSION_CLASSES': [
        'rest_framework.permissions.AllowAny',
    ],
    'DEFAULT_PAGINATION_CLASS': 'rest_framework.pagination.PageNumberPagination',
    'PAGE_SIZE': 10
}

Step 6: Create the Chats App
# Create the chats app
python manage.py startapp chats

Step 7: Register the Chats App
The chats app is already added to INSTALLED_APPS in the settings.py above.

Step 8: Create Initial Database
# Create initial migrations and database
python manage.py migrate

Step 9: Test the Setup
# Run the development server
python manage.py runserver

Visit http://127.0.0.1:8000/ in browser to see the Django welcome page.

Step 10: Verify Django REST Framework Installation
Create a simple test by adding a basic API view in chats/views.py
from rest_framework.decorators import api_view
from rest_framework.response import Response

@api_view(['GET'])
def api_overview(request):
    return Response({
        'message': 'Messaging App API',
        'endpoints': {
            'api-overview': '/api/',
            'admin': '/admin/'
        }
    })

Add this to chats/urls.py (create the file):
from django.urls import path
from . import views

urlpatterns = [
    path('api/', views.api_overview, name='api-overview'),
]

Include it in the main messaging_app/urls.py:
from django.contrib import admin
from django.urls import path, include

urlpatterns = [
    path('admin/', admin.site.urls),
    path('', include('chats.urls')),
]

Project Structure
Your project structure should look like this:
messaging_app/
├── manage.py
├── messaging_app/
│   ├── __init__.py
│   ├── settings.py
│   ├── urls.py
│   └── wsgi.py
└── chats/
    ├── __init__.py
    ├── admin.py
    ├── apps.py
    ├── models.py
    ├── tests.py
    ├── views.py
    └── migrations/
        └── __init__.py
Next Steps
Now I have a Django project with:

. Django REST Framework installed and configured

.Chats app created

.Basic project structure set up

.Database initialized

1. Run Migrations
Step 1 — Make migrations
python manage.py makemigrations

If everything is correct, Django will detect your models and generate migration files.

Common errors & fixes
Error	Cause	Fix
No changes detected	You forgot to register your app in INSTALLED_APPS	Add app to INSTALLED_APPS
AppRegistryNotReady	Circular import or wrong app structure	Check imports & ensure apps follow Django structure
FieldError	Mistyped field or invalid model option	Recheck model fields spelling & arguments
2. Apply migrations
python manage.py migrate

This applies all migrations to your database.

Common migration errors & solutions
Error	What it means	How to fix
OperationalError: no such table	Migration order broken	Delete faulty migration, re-run makemigrations
InconsistentMigrationHistory	DB and migrations don’t match	Reset DB or fake migrations (--fake)
IntegrityError	Null constraints or duplicate data	Adjust model default, or clear old DB data

If the project is new, easiest fix is sometimes:
rm db.sqlite3
rm app/migrations/00*.py
python manage.py makemigrations
python manage.py migrate

3. Run the server
python manage.py runserver

Server running at:
http://127.0.0.1:8000/
Common runserver errors
Error	Meaning	Fix
ModuleNotFoundError	Wrong import path	Use relative imports or correct app name
ImproperlyConfigured	Missing settings, bad middleware	Re-check settings.py
DisallowedHost	ALLOWED_HOSTS empty	Set ALLOWED_HOSTS = ["*"] for development
Port already in use	Another process using port	Use another port: runserver 8080
4. Test your application

Visit your endpoints:

/admin/

/api/v1/... (if you used versioning)

/api/properties/

/api/bookings/

Any custom routes you added
